u001b[0;31mNameError\u001b[0m: name 'plt' is not defined"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, x + 0, linestyle='solid')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 1, linestyle='dashed')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 2, linestyle='dashdot')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 3, linestyle='dotted');\n","\n","# For short, you can use the following codes:\n","plt.plot(x, x + 4, linestyle='-')  # solid\n","plt.plot(x, x + 5, linestyle='--') # dashed\n","plt.plot(x, x + 6, linestyle='-.') # dashdot\n","plt.plot(x, x + 7, linestyle=':');  # dotted"],"metadata":{"id":"nJjPcf6I98HK"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Adjusting the Plot: Axes Limits\n","\n","Matplotlib does a decent job of choosing default axes limits for your plot, but sometimes it's nice to have finer control. The most basic way to adjust axis limits is to use the *plt.xlim()* and *plt.ylim()* methods:"],"metadata":{"id":"DohhCgUM-GCi"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","plt.xlim(-1, 11)\n","plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5);"],"metadata":{"id":"zLkClHfYuAKs"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Reverse the Axis Limit\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","plt.xlim(10, 0)\n","plt.ylim(1.2, -1.2);"],"metadata":{"id":"A8BI5ZAd-apw"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["A useful related method is plt.axis() (note here the potential confusion between axes with an e, and axis with an i). The plt.axis() method allows you to set the x and y limits with a single call, by passing a list which specifies **[xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax] :**"],"metadata":{"id":"rAkItjID-TLp"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","plt.axis([-1, 11, -1.5, 1.5]);"],"metadata":{"id":"oEsxFh3P-uIZ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Labeling Plots\n","\n","As the last piece of this section, we'll briefly look at the labeling of plots: titles, axis labels, and simple legends.\n","\n","Titles and axis labels are the simplest such labels—there are methods that can be used to quickly set them:"],"metadata":{"id":"uZpaD3U5-7yg"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","plt.title(\"A Sine Curve\")\n","plt.xlabel(\"x\")\n","plt.ylabel(\"sin(x)\");"],"metadata":{"id":"t1RdiGykt-Ie"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["When multiple lines are being shown within a single axes, it can be useful to create a plot legend that labels each line type.\n","\n","Again, Matplotlib has a built-in way of quickly creating such a legend. It is done via the (you guessed it) **plt.legend()** method.\n","\n","Though there are several valid ways of using this, I find it easiest to specify the label of each line using the label keyword of the plot function:"],"metadata":{"id":"HDEtR7wg_R-a"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x), '-g', label='sin(x)')\n","plt.plot(x, np.cos(x), ':b', label='cos(x)')\n","plt.axis('equal')\n","\n","plt.legend();"],"metadata":{"id":"DjFXQOKItysJ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["In the object-oriented interface to plotting, rather than calling these functions individually, it is often more convenient to use the ax.set() method to set all these properties at once:"],"metadata":{"id":"j0r2Z_dV_czP"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["ax = plt.axes()\n","ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","ax.set(xlim=(0, 10), ylim=(-2, 2),\n","       xlabel='x', ylabel='sin(x)',\n","       title='A Simple Plot');"],"metadata":{"id":"lpnY0i2c_l1A"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Simple Scatter Plots\n","Another commonly used plot type is the simple scatter plot, a close cousin of the line plot. Instead of points being joined by line segments, here the points are represented individually with a dot, circle, or other shape.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"1CCChPts_3AK"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["rng = np.random.RandomState(0)\n","for marker in ['o', '.', ',', 'x', '+', 'v', '^', '<', '>', 's', 'd']:\n","    plt.plot(rng.rand(5), rng.rand(5), marker,\n","             label=\"marker='{0}'\".format(marker))\n","plt.legend(numpoints=1)\n","plt.xlim(0, 1.8);"],"metadata":{"id":"EVg0roofAFpe"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Scatter Plots with plt.scatter\n","\n","A second, more powerful method of creating scatter plots is the plt.scatter function, which can be used very similarly to the plt.plot function:"],"metadata":{"id":"9KTKYm8XA0A0"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.scatter(x, y, marker='o');"],"metadata":{"id":"WAt3Uy09A6xs"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Consider this code for scatter plot\n","\n","rng = np.random.RandomState(0)\n","x = rng.randn(100)\n","y = rng.randn(100)\n","colors = rng.rand(100)\n","sizes = 1000 * rng.rand(100)\n","\n","plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes, alpha=0.3,\n","            cmap='viridis')\n","plt.colorbar();  # show color scale"],"metadata":{"id":"pM-bqG5VBXi0"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Question Answer Section**"],"metadata":{"id":"uY_xiWD0Mxh6"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**1.List any 2 python APIs that are used for Plotting Graphs.**\n","\n","Two commonly used Python APIs for plotting graphs are:\n","\n","Matplotlib : A widely used Python library for creating static, animated, and interactive visualizations.\n","\n","Seaborn : A high-level data visualization API based on Matplotlib that provides attractive statistical graphics."],"metadata":{"id":"TqlPtWxbMz5n"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**2.Name 2 important machnisms used for accesssing Matplotlib API.**\n","\n","Two important mechanisms used to access the Matplotlib API are:\n","\n","Pyplot Interface : Provides MATLAB-like plotting functions such as plot(), scatter(), hist(), etc.\n","\n","Object-Oriented Interface : Uses figure and axes objects for more detailed and customizable p